<br>
Secretary Abraham:<br>
<br>
I am firmly opposed to the administration's efforts to extend the licenses of aging nuclear plants. No nuclear plant has ever operated to the end of its 40-year licensed life. Yet the administration is extending nuclear reactor licenses for an additional 20 years in an obvious attempt to bolster the finances of the nuclear industry.<br>
<br>
I also oppose the administration trying to foist a second generation of unsafe nuclear reactors upon American communities. Stop trying to pave the way for unsafe reactors that lack containment structures, the last line of defense between the public and the release of radiation into the environment and surrounding communities. Start investing in conservation and renewable energy-that's the real path toward a promising and secure future. <br>
____________________________________________<br>
<br>
A reactor without a containment vessel? To my knowledge no such reactor has been build in the United States, nor will such a reactor be build. And how are these reactors unsafe, aside from their claim that they would lack a containment vessel. I request comments relating to this letter. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/24/02 11:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=52.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Letter from Greenpeace</span><hr size=1> Allah forbid the day these radical greenies ever get the majority in government.  I guess if they had to choose they'd just rather tear down the nuke power plants and replace them with giant dirty smokestacks that leaves an eternal cloud of blackness and unhealthy particulants in the air.  Or better yet just leave everyone without power.  If it ever came down to voting for what kind of powerplant that gets built in my backyard, a coal burning one or a nuke one, I'll go with the nuke one.  Thankyou.   Hmmm, and when the greenies do get into power I wonder whose picture we'll have to hang on our walls and everywhere in public?  Lets see here the Chinese hang pictures of Chairman Mao everywhere, the Iraqis Saddam.  Will we have to hang pictures of Ralph Nader perhaps?  No telling whose pictures we'll be dusting off at the re-education camp.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=hamster>Hamster</A> at: 8/24/02 11:42:44 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 543<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/24/02 9:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=52.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Letter from Greenpeace</span><hr size=1> Discovery1 wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  A reactor without a containment vessel? To my knowledge no such reactor has been build in the United States, nor will such a reactor be build. And how are these reactors unsafe, aside from their claim that they would lack a containment vessel. I request comments relating to this letter. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->The PBMR was to be built without a containment and without an exclusion zone. That was to provide an economic justification for that type of reactor. WITH a containment and exclusion zone a PBMR would be as expensive (or more expensive) that other reactors (which have already failed in the marketplace).<br>
<br>
Since the US partner (and main potential customer) of PBMRs has bailed out and the, since 9/11, the NRC not going to license an unprotected plant, the concept is dead.<br>
<br>
As to &quot;no such reactor has been build in the United States&quot; (without a containment), that is not quite true.<br>
<br>
Even those WITH containments are not all alike. The common idea is that a containment is an hardened shell of reinforced concrete, many feet thick. This is what is called a &quot;dry containment vessel&quot;.<br>
<br>
Much of the US plants are NOT like that. Instead they are &quot;pressure suppression vessels.&quot;  They have only a flimsy thin shell. The steam escaping from an accident is bubbled through a pool of water or over ice. This is supposed to condense the steam and prevent high pressures. The GE Mark-I &quot;containments&quot; were estimated by the US NRC as having a greater than 90% chance of failing in a accident.<br>
<br>
BTW - even the &quot;dry containment&quot; requires water sprays, etc. and are only rated to so-called &quot;design-basis&quot; accidents, NOT a more severe accident.<br>
<br>
In any event, NO containment system is designed to withstand an aircraft impact or truck-bomb.<br>
<br>
Hamster.. I think you are doing a serious disservice to Greenpeace. I think you should give careful reading to their energy plans. Exactly where did you get you ideas about their energy plan? Did you simply make it up or have you made the effort to analyse the facts BEFORE broadbrush villification.<br>
